Model-building dataset and Validation dataset

# Total number of samples
N <- dim(df)[1]
split_ratio <- 0.75
# model-building dataset
mb_size <- N * split_ratio
mb_samp <- sample(1:N, mb_size, replace = F)
mb_set <- df[mb_samp, ]
head(mb_set)

The split_ratio above is defined as \(\text{split_ratio}=\frac{\text{size of model-building dataset}}{\text{total number of samples}}\).

Assign values to variables in model-building dataset and validation dataset

# Response Variable
mb_y <- mb_set$count
valid_y <- valid_set$count
# Quantitative Variables for model-building dataset
mb_temp <- mb_set$temp
mb_humid <- mb_set$humid
mb_wind <- mb_set$wind
mb_visib <- mb_set$visib
mb_dew <- mb_set$dew
mb_solar <- mb_set$solar
# Quantitative Variables for validation dataset
valid_temp <- valid_set$temp
valid_humid <- valid_set$humid
valid_wind <- valid_set$wind
valid_visib <- valid_set$visib
valid_dew <- valid_set$dew
valid_solar <- valid_set$solar
# Qualitative Variables for model-building dataset
mb_hour <- mb_set$hour
mb_rain <- mb_set$rain
mb_snow <- mb_set$snow

### Model Rain and snow look squished, so lets take the square root for a better fit. Typically the polynomial models only use integer exponents, but we experiment and discover using square root results in a higher adjusted \(R^2\).

fitPower <- lm(formula = mb_y ~ factor(mb_hour) + mb_temp + mb_humid + mb_dew + mb_solar + mb_rain + mb_snow + factor(mb_func) + factor(mb_season) + factor(mb_holiday) + factor(mb_weekday) + factor(mb_hour):mb_temp + I(mb_snow^(1 / 2)) + I(mb_rain^(1 / 2)))
bestFitPower <- stepAIC(fitPower, direction = "both")
